WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Hello everyone. Thanks for sticking around and being with us today. Justin and I are

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.280
super excited to be giving this talk. So we'll go ahead and kick things off by sharing how

00:00:14.280 --> 00:00:22.000
we use Python, R, and Shiny to capture, process, and visualize motion in our FOCAL system at

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:27.760
Ping. So if you're familiar at all with Ping, you might think of us as a golf company, but

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:32.720
what we really are, are an engineering company that just happens to make golf clubs. With

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:37.680
every product, we ask ourselves, how can we use our knowledge of physics and engineering

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:43.360
principles to improve golf club design and ultimately people's enjoyment of the game?

00:00:43.360 --> 00:00:48.320
So the process of making a club from an idea to manufacturing it to ultimately putting

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:52.840
it in a player's hands has changed greatly since our company's inception almost 60 years

00:00:52.840 --> 00:00:57.000
ago. So today we're going to talk a little bit about how the tools in R, Python, and

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:02.919
Shiny have made this process more streamlined for both our external consumers and our internal

00:01:02.919 --> 00:01:09.400
engineers. So to sort of walk through this entire workflow, we can give an example research

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:16.680
question that we might have, such as, which golf shaft is best for a player? So to sort

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:22.760
of give a wide overview, if you're not familiar with golf, a golf shaft is the component of

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:26.480
a club that connects where a player grips it at the top of the club to the club head

00:01:26.480 --> 00:01:31.440
at the bottom. We typically characterize them by a property called flex, where on

00:01:31.440 --> 00:01:36.320
one end of the spectrum we have like a regular flex. The properties here is that it typically

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:41.919
flies higher and is used by players who swing a little slower. And on the other end of the

00:01:41.919 --> 00:01:46.680
spectrum, we've got an extra stiff flex. It typically flies a little lower and is used

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:52.680
by players who swing pretty fast. Those are all sort of like general knowledge nuggets.

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:58.959
But how do we know if this holds for a specific player that we're trying to fit?

00:01:58.959 --> 00:02:03.559
So to give an example of this concept of flex, we have a few pictures here of our co-worker

00:02:03.559 --> 00:02:08.039
Chris. Chris happens to be one of the faster swing speed golfers at Ping, and he loads

00:02:08.039 --> 00:02:12.679
the club with a ton of force in his downswing. So this is after he's taken the club back

00:02:12.679 --> 00:02:17.559
from address to kind of the top of his backswing here, and just as he's getting ready to transition

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:22.779
to bring the club down towards impact. Now, when we give Chris something that's in our

00:02:22.779 --> 00:02:28.199
softer flex or regular flex category, he's going to create a lot of deflection. So the

00:02:28.199 --> 00:02:32.279
club is going to flex a lot. And when we give Chris something that's in our extra stiff

00:02:32.279 --> 00:02:38.399
flex category, he's going to create very little deflection. Now, to an extent, Chris is a

00:02:38.399 --> 00:02:42.639
bit of an outlier in terms of the general golf population with how fast he's swinging

00:02:42.639 --> 00:02:46.679
or how much he's loading the club here. But the important thing to consider is that all

00:02:46.679 --> 00:02:50.440
golfers load the shaft and load the club differently at this point, and these loading

00:02:50.440 --> 00:02:54.679
patterns should be well understood and measured to answer the question of which golf shaft

00:02:54.679 --> 00:02:59.479
is best for this player. So we're going to showcase how we utilize our high-tech motion

00:02:59.479 --> 00:03:05.679
capture system that we call Focal and leverage Posit Connect to answer this question. So

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:10.860
Focal is probably the most high-end and in-depth research tool that we have at Ping, and it

00:03:10.860 --> 00:03:14.479
essentially allows us to track the golfer's swing from the time they address the ball

00:03:14.479 --> 00:03:18.880
through that loading phase to just after impact. And we're doing this by tracking some

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:23.479
small reflective markers that we place along the club head and on the shaft to model the

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:28.279
club as a body as it moves through space. Focal is quite a bit different than some of

00:03:28.279 --> 00:03:32.119
the other performance measurement systems in golf. If you've ever watched golf on the

00:03:32.119 --> 00:03:35.399
weekends, they have the launch monitors that are kind of tracing the ball flight and what

00:03:35.399 --> 00:03:40.179
the ball is doing. But with Focal, we can actually see exactly how the golfer manipulated

00:03:40.179 --> 00:03:46.979
the club and got to impact. And to give some context to the amount of data that we capture

00:03:46.979 --> 00:03:51.419
with the system, every swing that we take generates around 40,000 data points, and that's

00:03:51.419 --> 00:03:56.339
raw positional data on all those little markers, some velocities and accelerations of the club

00:03:56.339 --> 00:04:00.660
head and the shaft, and then even metrics that compare those two together. And we've

00:04:00.660 --> 00:04:04.940
had a motion capture system at Ping since 2011, and in the last 12 years, we've had

00:04:04.940 --> 00:04:11.100
the opportunity to capture over 75,000 swings on the system. And this data set ranges from

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:16.579
tour pro golfers to collegiate golfers to golfers at Ping that are scratch handicap

00:04:16.579 --> 00:04:21.459
and golfers at Ping that swing a club maybe once or twice a year. All of this data really

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:26.420
helps us drive new product innovations and insights that consumers will see in products

00:04:26.420 --> 00:04:31.420
in the marketplace two, three, and even five years down the road.

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:34.859
Now prior to leveraging Posit Connect and kind of the shiny framework that we're using

00:04:34.859 --> 00:04:39.579
today, our workflow was pretty static, and it looked a little bit like this. We would

00:04:39.579 --> 00:04:45.660
capture data with the system, we'd export that data to a very flat CSV, and we'd store

00:04:45.660 --> 00:04:51.100
the data in a super flat table database. And then we would pull down that data in Excel

00:04:51.100 --> 00:04:56.260
and do a lot of our analysis on very discrete insights in maybe an A-B test scenario where

00:04:56.260 --> 00:05:01.339
we're trying to compare one club and how much it flexed on average to another club

00:05:01.339 --> 00:05:06.579
or how fast one club moved relative to the other club in that test. And these discrete

00:05:06.579 --> 00:05:11.339
insights are great, and they especially help us when we're trying to design new clubs,

00:05:11.339 --> 00:05:15.220
but unless you were one of the key stakeholders that was really in tune with the motion capture

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:20.380
system, it was a little bit harder for everybody in the company to access the full swing data,

00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:24.619
kind of that time series data, and leverage the power of that full swing tracking that

00:05:24.619 --> 00:05:30.220
we're getting. And we wanted a way to make this better. So today, our workflow with Posit

00:05:30.220 --> 00:05:35.420
Connect is much more powerful, it's much more streamlined, and it's much more dynamic than

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:39.980
it has been in the past. And it looks a little bit like this. So again, we start by capturing

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:45.339
data. We're doing the bulk of our processing of all that raw positional data in Python.

00:05:45.339 --> 00:05:49.380
Those Python scripts are run directly in the motion capture software itself, and we're

00:05:49.380 --> 00:05:55.820
using some packages like OpenCV to actually spatially map impact and identify where impact

00:05:55.820 --> 00:06:01.140
happened. Impact is kind of our key event to classify a swing there. All of our swing

00:06:01.140 --> 00:06:07.119
data is then exported into a JSON file format, and those files are then uploaded to our much

00:06:07.119 --> 00:06:13.899
more structured relational database that we're interfacing with via APIs. Some of those APIs

00:06:13.899 --> 00:06:17.619
go to feed our physics-based models, and from those physics-based models, we're actually

00:06:17.619 --> 00:06:22.339
able to directly generate a lot of our engineering insights. What's cool for us here is that

00:06:22.339 --> 00:06:26.420
we can take those insights that we generate and turn them into plumber APIs that feed

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:32.739
and power our consumer-facing apps and tools. We're generating a ton of internal reports

00:06:32.739 --> 00:06:38.559
via our markdown documents to give to engineers on more of a test level or key stakeholders

00:06:38.559 --> 00:06:42.459
that want to see certain data points in the lab. And we're heavily leveraging the Shiny

00:06:42.459 --> 00:06:47.459
Dashboard framework that's powered by things like the tidyverse and future and fur to do

00:06:47.459 --> 00:06:51.859
some cleaning of that time series data and then also some parallel processing and computing

00:06:51.859 --> 00:06:56.140
of that time series data to bring it down a lot quicker and make it very accessible.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:07:01.220
All of this ultimately leading to that shaft recommendation for the player. So I'm going

00:07:01.220 --> 00:07:04.619
to zoom in a little bit on what one of these Shiny Dashboards might look like in the lab

00:07:04.619 --> 00:07:09.739
and kind of walk through that process. And what's powerful about the Shiny Dashboard

00:07:09.739 --> 00:07:14.299
framework for us is that it allows us to extract these very dynamic insights almost

00:07:14.299 --> 00:07:19.019
immediately following a swing. So we can have a player come into the lab, take a series

00:07:19.019 --> 00:07:22.260
of swings, and then we can look at things like where that player hit the ball on the

00:07:22.260 --> 00:07:27.540
face of the club and go through some of their impact location tendencies with them. And

00:07:27.540 --> 00:07:32.019
then we can pull in that time series data and talk through where we see the club bending,

00:07:32.019 --> 00:07:36.019
how we see it bending, where we see it loading the most, and what this means for the player

00:07:36.019 --> 00:07:41.100
and their swing. And this allows us to take this really complex positional data and all

00:07:41.100 --> 00:07:45.339
these other data points and translate it in a way that the player and the coach understand

00:07:45.339 --> 00:07:49.299
and give them some of that feedback. And we can go through, try several different things

00:07:49.299 --> 00:07:54.820
in the lab, and open up that feedback loop to help them take this and make action on

00:07:54.820 --> 00:08:01.179
it. We can further take that player's specific data and compare that player to maybe a population

00:08:01.179 --> 00:08:06.260
of players on some density charts here. And then we can take that player's specific data

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:09.700
and combine it with the insights that we've generated behind the scenes to ultimately

00:08:09.700 --> 00:08:14.380
lead to that shaft recommendation. And what we love about this is that we're not just

00:08:14.380 --> 00:08:17.540
communicating a shaft recommendation to the player, but we're actually able to use the

00:08:17.540 --> 00:08:22.299
data to inform the player why we believe this shaft will help them play their best on the

00:08:22.299 --> 00:08:26.380
course. And it's fun to be a part of that and see how it really takes over in their

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:27.380
game.

00:08:27.380 --> 00:08:34.219
All right. Now, from a research perspective, we can take a step back and look at all of

00:08:34.219 --> 00:08:38.700
the data that Focal collects. We can move past that first step of identifying which

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:43.219
shaft produces the best performance outcome for a player and move on to the possibly more

00:08:43.219 --> 00:08:48.380
complicated analysis as to why. So, does changing the flex of the shaft meaningfully change

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:53.539
how that player swings or how they orient the clip they set impact? And if it does,

00:08:53.539 --> 00:08:58.619
how can we quantify these changes and use them to drive our design and fitting principles?

00:08:58.619 --> 00:09:04.380
So, in this, we can consider a sort of recent player test that we run within our Focal system

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:09.739
where players hit two clubs. One was a regular flex shaft and one was an extra stiff flex

00:09:09.739 --> 00:09:14.859
shaft. So, as Justin mentioned before, a test like this with 20 players will generate a

00:09:14.859 --> 00:09:18.460
massive amount of positional data for each of the markers on the clubs. We're going to

00:09:18.460 --> 00:09:22.539
go through that sort of workflow that he just talked about and put together a sort of nice

00:09:22.539 --> 00:09:26.580
little summary file for some of our engineers and stakeholders in the test that include

00:09:26.580 --> 00:09:31.099
the swing and performance metrics for every shot for every player. But some of our design

00:09:31.099 --> 00:09:34.859
engineers that maybe weren't as heavily involved need something that's a little easier to process

00:09:34.859 --> 00:09:40.859
visually. So, it helped them see both a player shot-to-shot variation between the two prototypes

00:09:40.859 --> 00:09:45.059
as well as the player-to-player variation within the test. We can utilize Shiny and

00:09:45.059 --> 00:09:49.179
then the Paws of Connect to create an app where any engineer can go. They can select

00:09:49.219 --> 00:09:55.179
a test, maybe a player or two to compare and look at specific metrics. So, this is an example

00:09:55.179 --> 00:10:00.299
of what a dashboard might look like. As you can see, it does report some like discrete

00:10:00.299 --> 00:10:03.859
metrics because our engineers do care about these numbers still and they are very useful

00:10:03.859 --> 00:10:09.020
to them. Something that's great about Shiny though is it allows for an even greater visual

00:10:09.020 --> 00:10:13.299
effect for that transient data. So, you can see these are two different players that were

00:10:13.299 --> 00:10:18.340
in that test and we can produce these graphs using the tools available on packages like

00:10:18.340 --> 00:10:23.179
gghighlight and ggiraffe. This gives engineers insight on how a player reacts to the club

00:10:23.179 --> 00:10:29.340
within the timeframe of the swing. So, something in golf that's really cool is that regardless

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:33.900
of a player's skill level, everyone's swing is very unique and different. So, these two

00:10:33.900 --> 00:10:39.900
players that we have graphed here are both very highly skilled, but we can see that both

00:10:39.900 --> 00:10:45.380
the magnitude, the maximum result in shaft flexion that we see and the time that it occurs

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:49.979
in the swing are very different. So, this sort of information being able to visualize

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:55.020
the focal data in this manner is really nice for our engineers and allows them to easily

00:10:55.020 --> 00:11:00.619
determine like where they should focus their research and development efforts. So, this

00:11:00.619 --> 00:11:04.820
sort of initial analysis and visualization is great for a specific test, the results

00:11:04.820 --> 00:11:08.820
of a single test, but what if we want to use this data in the future or look at the results

00:11:08.820 --> 00:11:14.179
of many tests? That's where R steps in and provides a sort of statistical framework that

00:11:14.179 --> 00:11:20.020
we need to analyze 10, 15, 20 years' worth of player testing data. So, within this, we

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:24.059
can see patterns emerge from prototype to prototype or patterns emerge out of specific

00:11:24.059 --> 00:11:28.739
player groups that we're testing. So, kind of continuing our example from the shaft test,

00:11:28.739 --> 00:11:32.979
and if we want to run a basic statistical analysis, we can run an SPM test on those

00:11:32.979 --> 00:11:38.380
two players. Here, the gray section represents a sort of significant difference that we see,

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:41.820
and so what we can get out of this is that there's, they're very different throughout

00:11:41.820 --> 00:11:44.859
the entire swing except for a period kind of, you know, in the middle part of their

00:11:44.859 --> 00:11:50.500
downswing and then at impact. So, there's no statistical difference or significant difference

00:11:50.500 --> 00:11:56.820
between the two shafts at impact. This is a really important finding for our engineers.

00:11:56.820 --> 00:12:02.419
Additionally, we can use the tools available and the DevTools package to create our own

00:12:02.419 --> 00:12:07.619
packages within Ping for all of the physics-based modeling and simulation that we do for club

00:12:07.619 --> 00:12:12.979
golf ball impact and golf ball flight, and then using these packages in conjunction

00:12:12.979 --> 00:12:18.460
with all of our historical testing data allows us to conduct virtual player tests where we

00:12:18.460 --> 00:12:22.700
can simulate how players will react to and perform with clubs without having to physically

00:12:22.700 --> 00:12:29.859
prototype them or run any tests. This is great for us and saves us time and money. So, now

00:12:29.859 --> 00:12:35.299
I've sort of covered our complete workflow with Focal from capturing and processing every

00:12:35.299 --> 00:12:39.659
data point with our cameras, going through Python, and then producing consumer and internal

00:12:39.659 --> 00:12:45.659
facing apps with R and Shiny. The combination of all of these programs with Posit has really

00:12:45.659 --> 00:12:50.260
allowed our company to streamline our research and development process and make it very smooth.

00:12:50.260 --> 00:12:55.299
So, thank you for attending. We're happy to be here and take any questions.

